04823nam a22005895i 9780226337883DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263378837 a10.7208/97802263378832doi  a(DE-B1597)524869  a(OCoLC)952338681  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBJ68.A53bP37 2017 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a170.974090342231 aParetsky, Sara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWords, Works, and Ways of Knowing :bThe Breakdown of Moral Philosophy in New England before the Civil War /cSara Paretsky. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter I. The Background of the Christian Scholar -- tChapter II. Reason, Revelation, and the Rise of Biblical Criticism -- tChapter III. The Christian Scholar Comes of Age -- tChapter IV. The Knowledge Explosion at Andover -- tChapter V. The Narration of the Creation in Genesis -- tChapter VI. The Breakdown of Moral Philosophy at Andover -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCrime writer Sara Paretsky is known the world over for her acclaimed series of mysteries starring Chicago private investigator V. I. Warshawski, now in its seventeenth installment. Paretsky's work has long been inflected with history-for her characters the past looms large in the present-and in her decades-long career, she has been recognized for transforming the role of women in contemporary crime fiction. What's less well-known is that before Paretsky began her writing career, she earned a PhD in history from the University of Chicago with a dissertation on moral philosophy and religion in New England in the early and mid-nineteenth century. Now, for the first time, fans of Paretsky can read that earliest work, Words, Works, and Ways of Knowing. Paretsky here analyzes attempts by theologians at Andover Seminary, near Boston, to square and secure Calvinist religious beliefs with emerging knowledge from history and the sciences. She carefully shows how the open-minded scholasticism of these theologians paradoxically led to the weakening of their intellectual credibility as conventional religious belief structures became discredited, and how this failure then incited reactionary forces within Calvinism. That conflict between science and religion in the American past is of interest on its face, but it also sheds light on contemporary intellectual battles. Rounding out the book, leading religious scholar Amanda Porterfield provides an afterword discussing where Paretsky's work fits into the contemporary study of religion. And in a sobering-sometimes shocking-preface, Paretsky paints a picture of what it was like to be a female graduate student at the University of Chicago in the 1970s. A treat for Paretsky's many fans, this book offers a glimpse of the development of the mind behind the mysteries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEthicsxStudy and teachingzNew EnglandxHistory. 0aLearning and scholarship - New England - History. 0aLearning and scholarshipzNew EnglandxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aParetsky, Sara1 aPorterfield, Amanda08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226337883423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780